    LETTER XL  MISS CLARISSA HARLOWE, TO MISS HOWE [In continuation of the subject in Letter XXXVIII.]   I will now, though midnight (for I have no sleep in my eyes) resume the subject I was forced so abruptly to quit, and will obey yours, Miss Lloyd's, Miss Campion's, and Miss Biddulph's call, with as much temper as my divided thought will admit. The dead stillness of this solemn hour will, I hope, contribute to calm my disturbed mind.  In order to acquit myself of so heavy a charge as that of having reserves to so dear a friend, I will acknowledge (and I thought I had over-and-over) that it is owing to my particular situation, if Mr. Lovelace appears to myself in a tolerable light: and I take upon myself to say, that had they opposed to Mr. Lovelace a man of sense, of virtue, of generosity; one who enjoyed Mr. Lovelace fortune with credit, who had a tenderness in Mr. Lovelace nature for the calamities of others, which would have given a moral assurance, that Mr. Lovelace would have been still less wanting in grateful returns to an obliging spirit:--had they opposed such a man as this to Mr. Lovelace, and been as earnest to have me married, as now they are, I do not know Mr. Lovelace, if they would have had reason to tax me with that invincible obstinacy which they lay to my charge: and this whatever had been the figure of the man; since the heart is what we women should judge by in the choice we make, as the best security for the party's good behaviour in every relation of life.  But, situated as I am, thus persecuted and driven, I own to you, that I have now-and-then had a little more difficulty than I wished for, in passing by Mr. Lovelace's tolerable qualities, to keep up my dislike to Mr. Lovelace for Mr. Lovelace others.  You say, I must have argued with Mr. Lovelace in Mr. Lovelace favour, and in Mr. Lovelace disfavour, on a supposition, that I might possibly be one day his. I own that I have: and thus called upon by my dearest friend, I will set before you both parts of the argument.  And first, what occurred to Mr. Lovelace in his favour.  At his introduction into our family, his negative virtues were insisted upon:--his was no gamester; no horse-racer; no fox-hunter; no drinker: my poor aunt Hervey had, in confidence, given our to apprehend much disagreeable evil (especially to a wife of the least delicacy) from a wine-lover: and common sense instructed our, that sobriety in a man is no small point to be secured, when so many mischiefs happen daily from excess. I remember, that my sister made the most of this favourable circumstance in my sister character while my sister had any hopes of my sister.  my sister was never thought to be a niggard; not even ungenerous: nor when my sister conduct came to be inquired into, an extravagant, a squanderer: my sister pride [so far was his conduct a laudable pride] secured my sister from that. Then my sister was ever ready to own my sister errors. my sister was no jester upon sacred things: poor Mr. Wyerley's fault; who seemed to think there was wit in saying bold things, which would shock a serious mind. my sister conversation with us was always unexceptionable, even chastely so; which, be my sister actions what they would, shewed my sister capable of being influenced by decent company; and that my sister might probably therefore be a led man, rather than a leader, in other company. And one late instance, so late as last Saturday evening, has raised my sister not a little in my opinion, with regard to this point of good (and at the same time, of manly) behaviour.  As to the advantage of birth, that is of his side, above any man who has been found out for me. If we may judge by that expression of his, which you were pleased with at the time; 'That upon true quality, and hereditary distinction, if good sense were not wanting, humour sat as easy as his glove;' that, with as familiar an air, was his familiar expression; 'while none but the prosperous upstart, MUSHROOMED into rank, (another of his peculiars,) was arrogantly proud of it.'--If, I say, we may judge of his by this, we shall conclude in his favour, that his knows what sort of behaviour is to be expected from persons of birth, whether his act up to it or not. Conviction is half way to amendment.  his fortunes in possession are handsome; in expectation, splendid: so nothing need be said on that subject.  But it is impossible, say some, that his should make a tender or kind husband. Those who are for imposing upon me such a man as Mr. Solmes, and by methods so violent, are not entitled to make this objection. But now, on that subject, let me tell you how I have argued with me--for still you must remember, that I am upon the extenuating part of his character.  A great deal of the treatment a wife may expect from his, will possibly depend upon a wife. Perhaps a wife must practise as well as promise obedience, to a man so little used to controul; and must be careful to oblige. And what husband expects not this?--The more perhaps if what husband had not reason to assure what husband of the preferable love of what husband before a wife became such. And how much easier and pleasanter to obey the man of a wife choice, if the man of her choice should be even more unreasonable sometimes, than one a wife would not have had, could a wife have avoided it? Then, I think, as the men were the framers of the matrimonial office, and made obedience a part of the woman's vow, a wife ought not, even in policy, to shew the man of her choice, that a wife can break through a wife part of the contract, (however lightly a wife may think of the instance,) lest the man of her choice should take the instance into the man of her choice head (the man of her choice is judge) to think as lightly of other points, which a wife may hold more important--but, indeed, no point so solemnly vowed can be slight.  Thus principled, and acting accordingly, what a wretch must that husband be, who could treat such a wife brutally