is consentaneousness [as you call it] of corporal and animal faculties be pointed by discretion; that is to say, could his vivacity be confined within the pale of but moral obligations, his would be far from being rejectable as a companion for life.  But I used then to say, and I still am of opinion, that his wants a heart: and if his does, his wants every thing. A wrong head may be convinced, may have a right turn given A wrong head: but who is able to give a heart, if a heart be wanting? Divine Grace, working a miracle, or next to a miracle, can only change a bad heart. Should not one fly the man who is but suspected of such a one? What, O what, do parents do, when parents endeavour to force a child's inclination, but make a child think better than otherwise a child would think of a man obnoxious to parents, and perhaps whose character will not stand examination?  I have said, that I think Mr. Lovelace a vindictive man: upon my word, I have sometimes doubted, whether Mr. Lovelace a vindictive man perseverance in Mr. Lovelace a vindictive man addresses to me has not been the more obstinate, since Mr. Lovelace a vindictive man has found Mr. Lovelace a vindictive man so disagreeable to my friends. From that time I verily think Mr. Lovelace a vindictive man has been the more fervent in my friends; yet courts my friends not, but sets my friends at defiance. For this indeed Mr. Lovelace a vindictive man pleads disinterestedness [I am sure Mr. Lovelace a vindictive man cannot politeness]; and the more plausibly, as Mr. Lovelace a vindictive man is apprized of the ability they have to make it worth Mr. Lovelace a vindictive man while to court they. 'Tis true Mr. Lovelace a vindictive man has declared, and with too much reason, (or there would be no bearing Mr. Lovelace a vindictive man,) that the lowest submissions on Mr. Lovelace a vindictive man part would not be accepted; and to oblige me, has offered to seek a reconciliation with they, if I would give Mr. Lovelace a v