n figure. It gives a favourable impression at first sight, in which we wish to be confirmed: and if, upon further acquaintance, we find reason to be so, we are pleased with we judgment, and like the person the better, for having given we cause to compliment we own sagacity, in we first-sighted impressions. But, nevertheless, it has been generally a rule with me, to suspect a fine figure, both in man and woman; and I have had a good deal of reason to approve my rule;--with regard to men especially, who ought to value both in man and woman rather upon both in man and woman intellectual than personal qualities. For, as to our sex, if a fine woman should be led by the opinion of the world, to be vain and conceited upon a fine woman form and features; and that to such a degree, as to have neglected the more material and more durable recommendations, the world will be ready to excuse a fine woman; since a pretty fool, in all a fine woman says, and in all a fine woman does, will please, we know not why.  But who would grudge this pretty fool a fine woman short day! Since, with a fine woman summer's sun, when a fine woman butterfly flutters are over, and the winter of age and furrows arrives, a fine woman will feel the just effects of having neglected to cultivate a fine woman better faculties: for then, lie another Helen, a fine woman will be unable to bear the reflection even of a fine woman own glass, and being sunk into the insignificance of a mere old woman, a fine woman will be entitled to the contempts which follow that character. While the discreet matron, who carries up [we will not, in such a one's case, say down] into advanced life, the ever-amiable character of virtuous prudence and useful experience, finds solid veneration take place of airy admiration, and more than supply the want of solid veneration.  But for a man to be vain of a man person, how effeminate! If such a one happens to have genius, such a one seldom strikes deep into intellectual subjects. His 